HIFIVE Analysis

Alec Xia

2024-07-31

1 Research Question

  • Is there a difference in the average rates of total symptoms between HEPA and control groups?

1.1 Context to Consider

  • Seasonality of cold, flu, and allergy symptoms
  • Random assignment to treatment and control
  • Small number of participants that may still lead to imbalances after random assignment
  • Participants were enrolled at different times of the year and participated for different durations

2 Analysis Flow

  • Using Generalized Additive Mixed-Effect Model (GAMM) to account for correlated data structure and to add a smoother for weeks.

2.1 Any covariates to include?

  • Examined whether the treatment and control groups are different in age, sex, insurance type, race, family education, household income, asthma (yes/no), allergies (yes/no), enrollment week (in calendar week), duration.
  • Decided to not include other covariates beside duration and enrollment week.

2.2 Starting Model

  • Model Equation: \[ log(\mu_{ij}) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 (duration)_{i} + \beta_2 (timing)_{i} + \beta_3 (treatment)_{i} + f_1(week_{ij}) + b_{0i} \]

where

\(i\) is the the \(ith\) participant, \(j\) is the \(jth\) repeated measurement

\(\beta_0\) = the population intercept;

\(\beta_1\) = main effect of duration (in weeks);

\(\beta_2\) = main effect of enrollment timing (in calendar weeks);

\(\beta_3\) = main effect of treatment;

\(f_1\) = a cubic spline with normal second derivative penalty;

\(b_0\) = individual participant random intercept.

  • Started with a Poisson GAMM using gamm4 package. The underlying engine for mixed effect model is lme4.
HIFIVE.long$Record.ID <- as.character(HIFIVE.long$Record.ID)
fit0 <- gamm4(TotSymptoms~duration + EnrlWk + HEPA + s(WkInProgram, bs = "cr"), random = ~ (1|Record.ID), data = HIFIVE.long, family = poisson(link = "log"))
plot(fit0$gam)

summary(fit0$mer)

2.3 Overdispersion

From a first glimpse, the data may not fit Poisson distribution:

ggplot(HIFIVE.long, aes(x = TotSymptoms)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, color = "black", fill = "white") + 
  facet_wrap(HIFIVE.long$WkInProgram~.)

  • Checked overdispersion of the Poisson GAMM model using squared Pearson residuals.
overdisp_fun <- function(model) {
    rdf <- df.residual(model)
    rp <- residuals(model,type="pearson")
    Pearson.chisq <- sum(rp^2)
    prat <- Pearson.chisq/rdf
    pval <- pchisq(Pearson.chisq, df=rdf, lower.tail=FALSE)
    c(chisq=Pearson.chisq,ratio=prat,rdf=rdf,p=pval)
}
overdisp_fun(fit0$mer)
##        chisq        ratio          rdf            p 
## 2.518648e+02 1.376310e+00 1.830000e+02 5.553721e-04
  • Pearson residuals showed overdispersion for Poisson GAMM.

2.4 Negative Binomial GAMM model

  • To remedy the overdispersion, I switched to use negative binomial GAMM to model the data.
  • gamm4 is currently restricted to using families specified in glmer or lmer, which requires specification of parameter \(\theta\) for the negative binomial model to initiate.
  • I followed the protocol used in glmer.nb, where I used ML estimation for \(\theta\) based on fitted poisson model. (MASS library: theta.ml) Then, I used ML estimated \(\hat{\theta}\) to initiate the negative binomial model.
mu <- fitted(fit0$mer)
y <- HIFIVE.long$TotSymptoms
th <- MASS::theta.ml(y, mu)
fit1 <- gamm4(TotSymptoms~duration + EnrlWk + HEPA + s(WkInProgram, bs = "cr"), random = ~ (1|Record.ID), data = HIFIVE.long, family = negative.binomial(theta = th[1], link = "log")) # refit to a negative binomial model
plot(fit1$gam)

  • Using Pearson residual tests, I did not see any more significant overdispersion in the negative binomial model.
overdisp_fun(fit1$mer)

2.5 Model Checking

For model checking, there are limited resources for GAMM. I used DHARMa package, which employs a simulation based approach for model checking. Briefly, the model checking works as follows:
  • I started with producing a set of simulated residuals, and plotting the residuals in uniform QQ plot and against predicted values.
library(DHARMa)
simulationOutput <- simulateResiduals(fit1$mer)
plot(simulationOutput) # Looks like the model fits well overall.

  • Then I examined the residuals against each predictor.
plotResiduals(simulationOutput, HIFIVE.long$duration, asFactor = F)

plotResiduals(simulationOutput, HIFIVE.long$EnrlWk, asFactor =  F)

plotResiduals(simulationOutput, HIFIVE.long$HEPA)

  • Lastly, I conducted formal tests against zero inflation and overdispersion.
testDispersion(simulationOutput)

## 
##  DHARMa nonparametric dispersion test via sd of residuals fitted vs.
##  simulated
## 
## data:  simulationOutput
## dispersion = 0.40103, p-value = 0.72
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
testZeroInflation(simulationOutput)

## 
##  DHARMa zero-inflation test via comparison to expected zeros with
##  simulation under H0 = fitted model
## 
## data:  simulationOutput
## ratioObsSim = 1.2592, p-value = 0.28
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
